    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-18T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-18T16:00:00-05:00" n="577"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d577">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/11641d: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-18T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 18, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>83. In view of the possibility of an early substantial increase in air transport
                    space between China and India, can you suggest further kinds of cargo in
                    addition to those raw materials now being transported. Are there supplies of
                    antimony, wood oil or other materials readily available for the purchase of
                    which it might now be worth while to consider arrangements?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
